<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-471-159  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 471 159.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>AI Expert  Oct 1990 v5 n10 p71(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Miller Freeman Publications 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Smart emergency monitoring. (Technology Application Inc's ReactorEmergency Action Level Monitor is being used to implement aprototype intelligent emergency monitoring system at SouthernCalifornia Edison's San Onofre, CA, nuclear power plant)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Technology Applications Inc. (products)Southern California Edison Co. (automation).andO;Ticker:    SCE.andO;Product:   Reactor Emergency Action Level Monitor (Computer program) (usage).andO;Topic:     Nuclear Power PlantsMonitorsEmergenciesSoftware PackagesUtilizationKnowledge-Based Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Engineers at Southern California Edison's San Onofre, Callf., nuclear powerplant are about to deploy an intelligent emergency-monitoring systemprototype in a research capacity.andP;  The prototype is an implementation of theReactor Emergency Action Level Monitor (REALM), developed by TechnotogyApplication Inc. of Jacksonville, Fla.andP;  REALM is designed to assist nuclearpower plant operators in the monitoring and classification of plantemergencies.andP;  The system runs on IBM compatibles and Digital Equipment Corp.andO;VAXs.andM;The San Onofre system, which will be installed soon at the plant simulator,will undergo intensive testing.andP;  Its ultimate goal is on-line integrationwith the main computer to interpret sensor data 24 hours a day.andP;  Theknowledge base contains information about plant operation, reasoning, sensorstates, and accepted strategies; it also captures custom knowledge relatingspecifically to the San Onofre plant's design and management practices.andM;During an emergency, the system will reason about possible explanations andclassify the event according to regulatory guidelines.andP;  According to CyrusAnderson, supervisor of site emergency planning at the San Onofre plant,&quot;Some emergency classification guidelines are monitored outside the controlroom and do not fall within the operator's normal area of responsibility...andO;REALM will monitor and report all conditions pertaining to emergencyclassifications.&quot; In this sense REALM serves as an advisor to the operator,who can reject the system's recommendations.andM;The San Onofre system will also respond to inquiries, perform  vulnerabilityanalysis&quot; (determining which procedures may aggravate an emergency), anddocument the flow of events.andP;  It can be used for emergency drills andemployee training in an off-line mode.andO;</TEXT></DOC>